WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.500
Hello everyone, welcome to the Grand Prequel Pod.

00:03.500 --> 00:07.780
This week we will be doing our preview of F1 Academy,

00:07.780 --> 00:12.700
which starts in China next weekend at the time of recording.

00:12.700 --> 00:18.200
Our hosts this week are Alex @monzabanking on Twitter,

00:18.200 --> 00:22.440
and Peter @ln4mcqueen on Twitter as well.

00:22.440 --> 00:29.380
I want to mention, which I think is really funny,

00:29.380 --> 00:33.040
is that we're filming this right on the International Women's Day,

00:33.040 --> 00:37.080
which is, you know, just a little nice fact of this.

00:37.080 --> 00:41.280
Yeah, I mean, apart from the fact we have no women recording.

00:41.280 --> 00:49.960
It is not my fault that I'm the biggest shooter for women in motorsports in this podcast group.

00:49.960 --> 00:53.700
Yeah, I guess we can just dive right into it.

00:53.700 --> 00:58.600
So, in PREMA, we have Peyton Westcott, Matilda Paatz,

00:58.760 --> 01:00.420
and Natalia Granada.

01:00.420 --> 01:03.260
Yeah, so I would start right out with Peyton Westcott,

01:03.260 --> 01:07.480
because I think she's genuinely considered one of the most interesting drivers.

01:07.480 --> 01:12.000
And if you saw recently on the F1 Academy Instagram,

01:12.000 --> 01:14.730
there was like a little post where they asked,

01:14.800 --> 01:18.640
Doriane Pin, Abbi Pulling, and Alice Powell,

01:18.640 --> 01:22.620
who they think will be doing best this season?

01:22.620 --> 01:24.640
Like, who's going to be a standout rookie?

01:24.640 --> 01:26.200
Who's going to be the biggest surprise?

01:26.200 --> 01:27.000
Who's going to be a champion?

01:27.000 --> 01:28.460
And I…

01:28.460 --> 01:30.780
So, Doriane Pin obviously mentioned her,

01:30.780 --> 01:34.600
because she's her replacement, you know, kinda, for Mercedes.

01:34.800 --> 01:40.460
But I think, in general, she's one of the drivers that are rated heavy,

01:40.460 --> 01:43.180
because she's with PREMA, she's with Mercedes,

01:43.180 --> 01:45.460
she's, you know, doing a lot of stuff.

01:45.460 --> 01:49.480
And if we look at how she did in Vegas last year,

01:49.480 --> 01:50.420
where she was a wild card,

01:50.420 --> 01:53.460
I think P6 in the sprint was not bad either.

01:53.620 --> 01:55.180
And I think, I don't quite remember,

01:55.180 --> 01:59.360
but I swear her main race was not that bad either.

01:59.360 --> 02:01.760
And I'd also like to add on,

02:01.760 --> 02:04.400
we have seen her in other F4 series.

02:04.400 --> 02:09.320
In Formula Trophy, in the, I think it was November, December time last year,

02:09.320 --> 02:10.190
she took her win.

02:10.190 --> 02:13.220
She was taking part in the F4 UAE with PREMA.

02:13.220 --> 02:15.120
Despite missing the last round,

02:15.120 --> 02:17.160
she was still quite consistent, I feel like,

02:17.160 --> 02:20.190
kind of in that, like, kind of the top end,

02:20.190 --> 02:23.020
just being outside of the points, getting a few points as well,

02:23.180 --> 02:24.400
which is a very good showing,

02:24.400 --> 02:28.460
because overall, the UAE4 field is quite competitive, I feel like.

02:28.460 --> 02:32.000
I mean, UAE4 was absolutely magnificent, if you ask me.

02:32.000 --> 02:36.900
What I want to point out is that it's heavily rumored that she will do,

02:36.900 --> 02:40.540
or is it even announced, that she will do a double campaign with PREMA,

02:40.540 --> 02:43.320
and will do Italian F4 again.

02:43.320 --> 02:45.280
But the thing is, I'm worried a bit,

02:45.280 --> 02:50.240
because I think she's one of those drivers that could really fight for wins and stuff already.

02:50.860 --> 02:57.720
But I don't know if PREMA is possible to support her in the way that it would be needed, you know?

02:57.720 --> 03:01.740
They've been the team's champion in the last three seasons.

03:01.740 --> 03:06.340
They've won the, you know, driver's championship twice.

03:06.340 --> 03:08.520
They should be able to do it again.

03:08.520 --> 03:11.620
But if you look at, I feel like even in UAE4,

03:11.620 --> 03:16.160
they were not necessarily as strong as they used to be in F4.

03:16.160 --> 03:17.140
Yeah, definitely.

03:17.140 --> 03:20.060
But at least with her, she also has this Mercedes support,

03:20.060 --> 03:22.340
which should also help her a lot,

03:22.340 --> 03:24.460
because I think with Doriane, they helped a lot.

03:24.460 --> 03:28.700
And yeah, I think another thing she may also a bit struggle with is just,

03:28.960 --> 03:34.040
in F1 Academy, the calendar circuit is so different to traditional F4 circuits.

03:34.040 --> 03:38.480
She has run more street races, so that may be more of a struggle for her.

03:38.480 --> 03:44.200
As a rookie, compared to returning drivers, who have years of experience on these tracks.

03:44.200 --> 03:49.860
But I think it'll be interesting to see how well she can do with also adjusting to these circuits.

03:49.920 --> 03:55.440
And I mean, you mentioned Mercedes has probably one of the best simulators.

03:55.440 --> 04:00.560
And I think they should be able to really help her out.

04:00.560 --> 04:05.600
And I think she should be one of the rookies that I expect to, like, be definitely-

04:05.600 --> 04:09.960
I think she's arguably even the rookie that I could expect really to be the highest.

04:09.960 --> 04:11.160
I agree, definitely.

04:11.160 --> 04:17.160
I want to move on to Matilda Paatz, because she's the one that I want to b-

04:17.160 --> 04:20.480
I want her to be the best rookie, because she's really dear to me.

04:20.480 --> 04:22.160
She's, you know, she's 17.

04:22.160 --> 04:22.890
She's German.

04:22.890 --> 04:28.980
She's supported by Aston Martin, which she didn't just get, you know, because she did anything.

04:28.980 --> 04:36.100
But as we found out some months ago, there was an Aston Martin shootout kind of test with Prema,

04:36.100 --> 04:39.660 
where they, you know, had like, I think it was five to seven girls.

04:39.660 --> 04:42.200
And there was also Lisa Blyard around and some others.

04:42.200 --> 04:44.240
And they let them drive.

04:44.240 --> 04:45.500
And she was the fastest.

04:46.080 --> 04:54.560
And that's how she got this backing, which is, I think, kind of proving my point that she has obviously quite a lot of experience.

04:54.560 --> 04:59.940
She has podiums in Central European Zone F4 and Formula Winter Series.

04:59.940 --> 05:06.260
She finished eighth last season in Central European Zone Formula 4.

05:06.260 --> 05:08.320
That's a horrific name, but whatever.

05:08.320 --> 05:18.660
And I'm unsure how the team she's with in that series can, you know, help her, because she's with Matilda Racing, the racing team that her father founded.

05:18.660 --> 05:21.820
And they're making their first steps into F4.

05:22.020 --> 05:28.180
So I think she's like, not even in one of the best teams in Central European Zone F4.

05:28.180 --> 05:30.700
So for that, I think she's doing really well.

05:30.700 --> 05:40.060
And she was around in Montreal, where I feel like last season was really sad, because Montreal was really not a good weekend.

05:40.060 --> 05:41.180
There was a lot of crashes.

05:41.180 --> 05:47.660
There was a lot of adjusting, because the track is not really suited for, you know, smaller single-seaters.

05:47.660 --> 05:51.820
And this, I think, she has retired twice.

05:51.820 --> 05:54.140
And her best finish was P11.

05:54.140 --> 06:02.460
It was kind of sad, but I think she should be the one in my heart who could really fight for the best rookie.

06:02.840 --> 06:13.980
One thing I'd like to add on is, even in, if she can have the best team in CEZ F1- F4 I mean, she's still good in that all-important track time.

06:13.980 --> 06:18.660
And at the F4 level, it's just, you just need to be getting those laps in the car.

06:18.660 --> 06:22.820
And that experience can hopefully help her bring pace to the other races.

06:22.820 --> 06:26.040
And it's all a learning curve in this level of racing.

06:26.160 --> 06:27.220
Yeah, I mean, I agree.

06:27.220 --> 06:33.020
But the last point that I wanted to point out is, she's with Aston Martin, which does worry me a bit.

06:33.020 --> 06:38.340
Because I had high hopes that just because she's German, she would get picked up by Mercedes.

06:38.340 --> 06:39.340
Or even Audi.

06:39.340 --> 06:43.000
I mean, Audi was pretty clear that they would stay with Emma Felbermayr.

06:43.000 --> 06:48.140
But the point for me is, Aston Martin recently had Tina Hausmann.

06:48.140 --> 06:50.180
And who was it before her?

06:50.180 --> 06:51.320
Oh, she was Prema?

06:51.320 --> 07:00.500
No, because I swear they had, was it Jessica Hawkins, who they, not supported in F1 Academy necessarily, but who they, you know, worked with.

07:00.500 --> 07:03.940
Yeah, no, she's on Sky, I see on Sky Sports and stuff sometimes.

07:03.940 --> 07:18.840
And the problem is that Aston Martin, with both of these drivers, was a bit, they were criticized because they did not really develop, especially Tina Hausmann, in any, you know, big way.

07:18.840 --> 07:24.900
Because it should have been a possibility to, for her, especially in her second season, to become better.

07:24.900 --> 07:32.020
And, you know, there was often Jessica Hawkins around, but it didn't feel like they were doing any impact.

07:32.020 --> 07:41.200
At the same time, Emma Feblermayr has the same kind of support with Carrie Schreine, but it felt like they were doing a lot more.

07:41.540 --> 07:46.420
And, I mean, Emma Feblermayr was also doing, like, a double campaign, while Tina Hausmann didn't.

07:46.420 --> 07:50.800
And we don't know how much of that is a lack of funding.

07:50.800 --> 08:01.700
But I really hope that Matilda Paatz will also get the support when she does Central European Zone F4, technically on her own.

08:01.960 --> 08:13.560
But if she gets support by Aston Martin, you know, I mean, the tracks to drive it, I don't think, I think only the Red Bull Ring should be, you know, familiar to the F1 team.

08:13.560 --> 08:16.100
But I hope they support her more.

08:16.520 --> 08:26.680
Yeah, and then the final driver for PREMA is Natalia Granada, who's expected to be with Weller in terms of, like, her support, in a way.

08:26.680 --> 08:30.740
But I think she is kind of the least experienced out of all of them.

08:30.740 --> 08:34.580
But she does have an Iron Dames connection, I believe.

08:34.580 --> 08:39.280
Yeah, I mean, the drivers I mentioned so far, Peyton Westcott has a full season.

08:39.280 --> 08:42.120
I think Matihilda Paatz even has two full seasons in F4.

08:42.120 --> 08:45.880
Natalia Granada, at 18, she's the oldest out of the bunch,

08:46.410 --> 08:51.380
will make her single-seater debut only here.

08:51.380 --> 09:06.760
She finished in the rookie tests 7th and 8th, which can be kind of put down to the fact that she's one of the few out of the rookie tests who, you know, has either never really driven a single-seater car before or hasn't done a lot of testing.

09:06.760 --> 09:11.140
Which maybe she actually did with Iron Dames, but I haven't heard of it.

09:11.140 --> 09:14.100
Yeah, but I think she started karting a bit later.

09:14.200 --> 09:18.040
She started at 11, compared to, you know, typically she started a lot younger.

09:18.040 --> 09:22.440
So maybe that explains why she was making her F4 debut a bit later as well.

09:22.520 --> 09:29.720
I could imagine what I saw is that, she was doing also like sports cars and trying it out.

09:29.720 --> 09:35.900
And I could imagine it's really for her, also the fact that sponsoring is so difficult still,

09:35.900 --> 09:46.640
because if you do not come from a wealthy family, if you do not come from a country that's really, that has, you know, huge setups to support you.

09:46.640 --> 09:51.240
It's really difficult to still find that first sponsoring..

09:51.460 --> 09:56.340
Even at the lower F4 series, it still gets like crazy expensive.

09:56.340 --> 09:58.500
It makes it so hard for drivers.

09:58.500 --> 10:02.020
And yeah, hopefully, I mean, I believe in rookie testing.

10:02.020 --> 10:03.460
She was doing decently.

10:03.460 --> 10:08.170
So I mean, we won't truly know until China because testing is testing.

10:08.410 --> 10:15.020
To be fair, out of the drivers that we only know from the rookie test, I think she was actually the worst.

10:15.020 --> 10:19.550
And she was like the worst that was still picked, which makes me worry a bit.

10:19.550 --> 10:28.740
Because everyone was kind of hoping for Alexia Danielsson, who, you know, was also rookie testing and finished just above her, would get a seat.

10:28.740 --> 10:31.200
But, you know, we don't know what happens behind the scenes.

10:31.200 --> 10:33.400
And that's what makes me a bit nervous.

10:33.400 --> 10:39.040
Because in every other F4 series, we know, you know, drivers approach teams, teams approach drivers.

10:39.040 --> 10:41.720
It's like, “hey, I have money, I can pay.”

10:41.720 --> 10:47.140
With F1 Academy, you have this as part of the livery sponsor.

10:47.670 --> 10:51.160
And it confuses me just a little bit how they do it.

10:51.160 --> 10:56.780
And it seems to be really kind of, I mean, it seems really, really weird at times.

10:56.780 --> 11:03.980
I think she's the one who I'm kind of the most concerned about maybe, because she definitely is the rookie with the least experience.

11:03.980 --> 11:07.900
Because all of the others have some sort of F4 experience before.

11:07.900 --> 11:12.120
But she doesn't have much and it's a massive unknown for her.

11:12.240 --> 11:17.980
I think we'll see because I think her backing with the Iron Dames should really support her.

11:17.980 --> 11:20.340
Because, you know, they have experience.

11:20.340 --> 11:23.340
And they have had her testing karts before.

11:23.340 --> 11:26.160
I saw on her Instagram so recently, she's been testing.

11:26.160 --> 11:29.480
The question is just how much experience can she do?

11:29.560 --> 11:40.520
And I expect her to do the worst out of PREMA because, you know, everyone else is kind of this person who already got a lot of experience or is with great teams and has similar sessions.

11:40.520 --> 11:42.080
She will be with Wella.

11:42.080 --> 11:46.220
What she was supposed to do, like, she really starts on the backfoot..

11:47.280 --> 11:49.800
Very contrasting to the Campos lineup.

11:49.800 --> 11:52.440
Alisha Palmowski, backed by Red Bull.

11:52.440 --> 11:55.020
One of the title favorites, I would say.

11:55.020 --> 11:58.900
I want to crash out about Alisha Palmowski for a second here.

11:58.900 --> 12:03.220
Because she is by far my favorite driver out of this series.

12:03.220 --> 12:04.900
And it's very important for me.

12:04.900 --> 12:07.580
Because I want to tell a little story,

12:07.580 --> 12:09.620
because she was in 2024.

12:09.920 --> 12:13.180
she was the wildcard driver for Qatar, I think it was.

12:13.180 --> 12:16.880
And before, they were doing mid-season testing.

12:16.880 --> 12:22.180
And at the time, there was only, like, you know, unnamed driver who will be the wildcard.

12:22.180 --> 12:23.900
And I took it upon myself.

12:23.900 --> 12:25.300
And I found out it was her.

12:25.300 --> 12:28.060
And since that day, I've been her biggest fan.

12:28.060 --> 12:32.820
Because she's been so far incredible in the things that she has done.

12:32.820 --> 12:36.380
Last year, she was P5 in F1 Academy.

12:36.380 --> 12:37.920
Like, second best rookie.

12:38.300 --> 12:43.100
And I think some of it can be traced down to the fact that she had Chloe Chambers on her team.

12:43.100 --> 12:45.160
Who was obviously even more in the fight.

12:45.160 --> 12:46.740
Who was more experienced in F1 Academy.

12:46.740 --> 12:49.800
And they kind of took points from each other at times.

12:49.800 --> 12:53.840
Where Ella Lloyd, you know, was pretty much by far the best in her team.

12:53.840 --> 12:57.200
And didn't really have anyone to fight with in her own team.

12:57.200 --> 12:58.640
But what I really want to point out.

12:58.640 --> 12:59.740
And what I'm still mad about,

12:59.740 --> 13:03.500
is that in 2024, she was runner-up in GB4.

13:03.500 --> 13:05.040
With multiple wins.

13:05.040 --> 13:06.240
You know, podiums.

13:06.240 --> 13:06.860
Everything.

13:07.180 --> 13:10.640
And GB4 introduced a thing that I still think is beautiful.

13:10.640 --> 13:12.800
And I thank GB4 for it every day.

13:12.800 --> 13:16.260
in which they give a certain amount of money

13:16.260 --> 13:20.040
as sponsoring towards an F1 Academy suit.

13:20.040 --> 13:21.880
And it sounds not like a lot.

13:21.880 --> 13:26.620
But I swear for her, Alicia was like £30,000 pounds or something.

13:26.740 --> 13:33.000
And that's a huge sum for a driver who's pretty much gone through her entire career this far,

13:33.000 --> 13:38.960
just on scholarships and money she's kind of made by proving her worth.

13:38.960 --> 13:43.480
Next to Jamie Chadwick, she's the only one to earn the Ginetta Junior scholarship.

13:43.480 --> 13:45.480
Which she did like back in 2022.

13:45.480 --> 13:47.780
And she was pretty good in Ginetta’s too.

13:47.780 --> 13:51.920
She's really someone who I think is an incredible driver.

13:51.920 --> 13:53.300
And I'm really sad though,

13:53.300 --> 13:59.000
because she's sadly pretty old considerably for F4 already at 19 years old.

13:59.580 --> 14:03.540
And you know, F1 is not in the cards anymore.

14:03.540 --> 14:08.360
Especially because even if she wins the season and gets seats sponsored for FRECA,.

14:08.360 --> 14:11.780
she would need to somehow find money there,

14:11.780 --> 14:16.300
because she's one of those drivers that seems to really not be favored by sponsors.

14:16.300 --> 14:19.020
Which I think is super, super disappointing.

14:19.020 --> 14:20.440
Because look what she does.

14:20.820 --> 14:22.820
Funnily enough, I would say.

14:22.820 --> 14:25.360
Even though she's one of the older ones,

14:25.360 --> 14:27.000
she's actually youngest on her team.

14:27.000 --> 14:31.200
And she's still considered by far, you know, the favorite for the team.

14:31.200 --> 14:32.440
She will be the favorite.

14:32.440 --> 14:38.740
And you know, the predictions I mentioned earlier with Doraine Pin, Abbi Pulling and Alice Powell,

14:38.740 --> 14:41.860
all of them said that she would win this championship,

14:41.860 --> 14:43.140
and I think so too,

14:43.140 --> 14:44.220
and I hope so.

14:44.220 --> 14:48.980
Because if she doesn't, I really worry for what will become of her career,

14:48.980 --> 14:52.060
because I think she could do also great in other series.

14:52.060 --> 14:55.520
But I would love for her to be able to go to GB3.

14:55.520 --> 15:00.420
Which, in my opinion, she should have been able to do after 2024.

15:00.420 --> 15:08.140
How do you come, run her up in the championship and not be able to get sponsored to move up?

15:08.140 --> 15:10.080
It just doesn't make sense to me.

15:10.080 --> 15:11.240
I've seen it.

15:11.240 --> 15:16.660
Boys from the series, they can place 10th without a single podium or win,

15:16.660 --> 15:19.220
they can get sponsors to go to GB3.

15:19.220 --> 15:21.180
She's runner up.

15:21.180 --> 15:23.720
she won her first ever single-seater race,

15:23.720 --> 15:25.740
but she cannot get the sponsor.

15:25.740 --> 15:27.460
I think it's horrific.

15:27.460 --> 15:31.560
I think the main hope for her is for 2027 to target GB3.

15:31.560 --> 15:35.960
And she is probably one of the drivers who impressed me the most last year.

15:36.500 --> 15:42.580
Like, as you said, her and Chambers were taking points off each other, whereas Lloyd was the lead driver in her team.

15:42.580 --> 15:47.000
But yeah, I think she has a lot to prove this season, and I'm excited to see it.

15:47.000 --> 15:51.260
And then, alongside her, we have Rafaela Ferreira,

15:51.720 --> 15:53.660
she's 20 years old with VCARB.
.
15:53.660 --> 15:56.960
She struggled quite a bit last year.

15:56.960 --> 15:58.640
she finished 12th overall.

15:58.640 --> 16:02.960
And the year before, she did Brazil F4.

16:02.960 --> 16:05.640
And all of those, she did take three wins.

16:05.640 --> 16:08.400
all of those wins were at one track.

16:08.800 --> 16:11.300
So, I would say it…

16:11.300 --> 16:12.400
We should go to that track.

16:12.400 --> 16:13.340
Yeah.

16:13.340 --> 16:19.080
To be fair, F4 and Interlagos, that would be a great weekend to have at F1 Academy.

16:19.080 --> 16:20.220
That would be beautiful, actually.

16:20.220 --> 16:21.920
If money wasn't an issue…

16:21.920 --> 16:27.100
When I think about her, I wonder how far the…

16:27.100 --> 16:29.540
I mean, she was doing fairly poorly last season.

16:29.540 --> 16:33.640
she was by far the weakest link in the Campos lineup.

16:33.640 --> 16:36.340
And I wonder how far the problem was.

16:36.860 --> 16:42.620
If she's just, you know, not a great driver, which, you know, we can't already say that.

16:42.620 --> 16:43.640
I feel horrible for saying it.

16:43.640 --> 16:46.840
Or, and I could really imagine that being the problem.

16:46.840 --> 16:56.640
If it's the problem that she's moving on from F4 Brazil, you know, she comes from this South American national championship,

16:56.640 --> 17:04.900
which is incredibly different to being in F1 Academy, which is in different cars, internationally,

17:05.180 --> 17:08.680
different circuits, different, you know, race, how they work.

17:08.680 --> 17:10.110
A totally different grid.

17:10.110 --> 17:16.180
And I think this could be one of the things that I worry about for her.

17:16.180 --> 17:23.240
Because as a Brazilian, she will always have it more difficult than someone located in, especially Great Britain.

17:23.240 --> 17:29.140
Because for some reason, Great Britain is really up on top with those few drivers too.

17:29.140 --> 17:35.850
But I really hope that she will be able to, you know, kind of take that experience that she made last season.

17:35.850 --> 17:38.740
And the last season that really, it was not great.

17:38.740 --> 17:40.540
It was very difficult.

17:40.540 --> 17:41.400
she was struggling.

17:41.520 --> 17:52.680
And I hope that we can trace it back to the fact that moving from Brazil to international racing is just a really difficult step for everyone.

17:52.680 --> 18:06.520
Not just for her, but for every single male driver that moves from an F4 series that's like local to a country that's unusually represented on feeder series calendars.

18:06.680 --> 18:08.080
It's always difficult.

18:08.080 --> 18:14.780
Then finally at Campos, we have Megan Bruce, who is in the Tag Heuer car.

18:14.780 --> 18:17.720
She did race a bit last year,

18:17.720 --> 18:20.520
she was a replacement at Singapore.

18:21.400 --> 18:30.220
And she finished P12 and P13 respectively in each races, which I would say it's decent given her kind of a last minute stand in.

18:30.220 --> 18:40.880
I think she's interesting because I remember from her last season that she was doing GB4 in hopes of, kind of gaining that female driver's trophy.

18:41.040 --> 18:58.040
So she could reach F1 Academy, but I feel like Tag Heuer majorly picked her up, after she was the injury replacement at Singapore instead, which is fine because she did, as far as I remember, she missed a GB4 round.
18:58.040 --> 19:03.500
And because of that, she missed the female trophy, which she was leading up until that point.

19:04.350 --> 19:07.180
And for her, I think, again, it's a bit sad.

19:07.180 --> 19:08.060
She's 21.

19:08.060 --> 19:11.260
She's realistically not really doing any moves.

19:11.260 --> 19:18.380
And she's one of those drivers where I'm like, it would have been great to see her on the grid, say, five years ago.

19:18.740 --> 19:35.940
But also, and what I think is really interesting about her, I swear, I read somewhere that she mentioned that F1 Academy was like the first time she was really, that she saw it was like possible to, for even girls to, you know, get further into single series, really do it.

19:35.940 --> 19:38.820
Because before that, she was doing other series.

19:38.820 --> 19:44.780
I don't quite remember what she was doing, but it was not single series and she was really into karting and stuff.

19:44.780 --> 19:54.380
And that's like, I think it helped, I assume that it helped her gain the confidence and sponsors to be able to reach F1 Academy at this point.

19:54.380 --> 19:57.920
Which is, I think, a sign that F1 Academy is working.

19:57.920 --> 20:08.260
We have this huge increase of women who see the opportunity and also brands seeing the opportunity that there is a place to move up.

20:08.260 --> 20:10.460
Do we want to continue to MP?

20:10.980 --> 20:17.850
Yeah, so MP have Nina Gademan, Alba Larson and Esmee Kosterman racing for them.

20:17.850 --> 20:21.500
Nina Gardeman, 20 years old, with Alpine.

20:21.500 --> 20:28.520
I mean, for me, she's pretty much the exact same conversation as we had with Megan Bruce.

20:28.520 --> 20:33.260
She's, I think, she did really great in some races.

20:33.260 --> 20:42.720
I think, especially 2024, she had some really, really standout performances, which is why I was kind of happy to see her on the F1 Academy grid.

20:42.720 --> 20:44.020
But she's 20.

20:44.020 --> 20:48.440
I would have loved if she was 16 and doing this.

20:48.610 --> 20:56.640
But from her career, I remember reading that, as far as I remember, she was racing at some point, but had to step away because of funding issues.

20:56.640 --> 21:08.280
And only was able to, you know, go back and afford it because of this rise in sponsorship for female drivers in British F4 and now F1 Academy.

21:09.960 --> 21:18.280
I want to point out something, which, she had the preseason accident in China last season where she was really hurt.

21:18.280 --> 21:23.850
And at times we were even worried that she wouldn't be able to, you know, go racing again.

21:23.850 --> 21:30.180
Because as far as I remember, it was, she hurt like, what was it, her spine, I think.

21:31.460 --> 21:39.300
And in Zandvoort, in her home race, she had to miss, I think it was free practice because she was in pain.

21:39.300 --> 21:48.960
And that really made it worse for me, because I know she would have been able to perform even better if that was not the case.

21:48.960 --> 21:58.540
I think she could’ve been up in the conversation with Ella and Alicia if it was not for that, you know, crash and that injury.

21:58.900 --> 22:04.600
It's a fair point to make because this sport, people forget how dangerous it can be.

22:04.600 --> 22:08.960
And having something like a mass- it will take a huge amount of toll on you.

22:08.960 --> 22:11.840
I mean, it's perfectly natural, I think.

22:11.840 --> 22:19.180
And you would kind of maybe have that element of doubt creeping in in the way that, “oh, that happened last time, do I really want to push it so hard here?”

22:19.180 --> 22:25.140
I think she was able, especially towards the end of last season, we saw her improve really hard.

22:25.140 --> 22:33.040
And I think she was able to, you know, physically get well, but also just improve her racing.

22:33.040 --> 22:41.180
And I think it's great that she does not like have any sort of, you know, fear or any sort of worry that will hold her from racing.

22:41.180 --> 22:45.960
But I really hope that in the next season, she will be able to really show what she's able to be.

22:46.300 --> 22:50.960
For me, she was one of the most exciting rookies.

22:50.960 --> 22:54.780
And she was one of those drivers that I expected to do incredibly well,

22:54.780 --> 23:00.400
and it was so disappointing to see that being taken away from her for none of her own fault, really.

23:00.560 --> 23:07.640
Yeah, so hopefully, you know, we can see and kind of get her confidence back, you know, to a new season, a fresh start.

23:07.640 --> 23:17.960
And hopefully she can be up there with even like Alba Larson, her teammate, who, again, I'd say she has a lot of potential to step up.

23:17.960 --> 23:21.000
She is quite popular as well, I would say.

23:21.000 --> 23:22.020
She's with Ferrari.

23:22.020 --> 23:25.480
She's doing a double campaign with British F4.

23:25.480 --> 23:26.700
She's another big name.

23:27.020 --> 23:29.780
I don't quite think she would be in a title fight.

23:29.780 --> 23:32.220
I think that would be Palmowski and Lloyd.

23:32.220 --> 23:36.460
But I do expect her to maybe get a win or so here and there.

23:36.460 --> 23:40.540
I think Ferrari should be really, really great for her.

23:40.540 --> 23:47.740
Because I've pointed it out some time ago that Ferrari is one of those drivers, I mean, that I really like.

23:47.740 --> 23:50.700
Because you know that they support the drivers,

23:50.700 --> 23:56.760
you can see it in the way that they show up and the way that they do like training camps,

23:56.840 --> 23:59.120
and the way that they really, really involve the drivers.

23:59.120 --> 24:03.440
And I think that's something that Alba Larsen probably really needed.

24:03.440 --> 24:05.100
Because she's pretty young.

24:05.100 --> 24:09.500
She also looks pretty small, in my opinion.

24:09.500 --> 24:17.000
And so it's really difficult probably for her to pull up the amount of muscles that you need to drive that car.

24:17.000 --> 24:25.920
But I expect her with the support of Ferrari and, you know, the trainers and all that health stuff that comes with it,

24:25.920 --> 24:28.500
that she could really improve this season.

24:28.500 --> 24:36.300
And I think it's really sad for her that, you know, you have Ella Lloyd and Alicia Palmowski who both shouldn't be here.

24:36.340 --> 24:38.780
Because I think they should be at least in GB3.

24:38.780 --> 24:44.900
Because usually Alba Larson is the kind of driver that I think F1 Academy should be targeting,

24:44.900 --> 24:46.400
and who should be winning.

24:46.400 --> 24:52.780
And she would be winning if she wasn't going up against drivers who have like a bunch of more seasons of experience.

24:52.780 --> 24:55.480
Who are a lot older, you know.

24:55.540 --> 24:59.200
Who have so much support throughout the years that they've been able to.

24:59.200 --> 25:03.200
They've outgrown F4 in any way but physical.

25:03.200 --> 25:04.760
Yeah, and yeah.

25:04.760 --> 25:07.120
She did improve a lot last year.

25:07.120 --> 25:08.500
Like, she showed throughout the season.

25:08.500 -->  25:12.200
And I mean, didn't she take pole at Vegas or something?

25:12.200 --> 25:13.160
No.

25:13.160 --> 25:16.640
Pretty much all pole positions go on to Chloe Chambers.

25:16.640 --> 25:20.240
But she, I think she qualified on P2 or P3 or something.

25:20.240 --> 25:21.140
Yeah, I remember.

25:21.140 --> 25:23.260
Unfortunately, the race didn't go her way.

25:23.360 --> 25:26.760
But I remember her doing quite a strong quality performance.

25:26.760 --> 25:29.640
And she improved a lot as the year went on.

25:29.640 --> 25:34.120
She was also really, really consistent if I remember correctly.

25:34.120 --> 25:46.980
Because I swear that when I did the statistics, I realized that if we talk about like really proper rookie drivers.

25:46.980 --> 25:51.760
Drivers who haven't, you know, done as much before this.

25:52.160 --> 25:55.520
She was like by far the best out of the bunch.

25:55.520 --> 26:03.420
And also, if we only count like the F1 Academy rookies, she would have been the third best.

26:03.420 --> 26:10.420
But in the actual standings, including everyone else, Nina Gademan takes that point.

26:10.420 --> 26:21.480
Because at some point, you know, the points become so difficult that even if she was really consistent and often finished, like I think P5 and P7,

26:22.380 --> 26:27.540
if you take that away and you only count the rookies, she's like third best rookie quite often.

26:27.540 --> 26:30.800
She is definitely one to watch the season, I think.

26:30.800 --> 26:37.260
And then finally, we have Esmee Kosterman, who also I think is quite solid.

26:37.660 --> 26:41.020
She did choose the Zandvoort wildcard last year.

26:41.020 --> 26:43.460
And she was the best performing wildcard.

26:43.600 --> 26:55.260
I remember seeing her in Zandvoort the weekend prior, not the weekend prior, but some weekends prior when she was doing British F4, which a lot of F1 Academy drivers did that weekend.

26:55.260 --> 27:01.880
Because, you know, they were preparing for Zandvoort and they were getting their mileage wherever they could.

27:01.880 --> 27:09.500
And I think she was pretty solid even in Zandvoort back then, because even in the mixed field, she was doing pretty fine.

27:09.500 --> 27:16.040
Again, my only thought about her is, I wish she could have been here like a few years earlier.

27:16.040 --> 27:16.800
She's 20.

27:16.800 --> 27:21.940
Just imagine if she was able to do the same, but at like 16, 17.

27:21.940 --> 27:25.020
It would be glorious and I would really root for her, I think.

27:25.140 --> 27:38.480
She seemed to me to take it really serious and to really take the chance after moving from some championships that I have never heard of, like the Ford Fiesta Spring Cup Benelux.

27:38.480 --> 27:47.440
I don't know what that is, but I think it proves that she's one of those who- she wants to race and she races everything she can.

27:47.440 --> 27:53.740
And it's such a shame that just because she's a woman, she's not getting the support any male doing the same would get.

27:53.740 --> 28:05.380
I think it's pretty cool she's with a brand like Lego and it seems like Lego are doing quite a bit as well, because, you know, even one of the Speed Champions is now her F1 Academy car.

28:05.380 --> 28:06.580
I will be buying that.

28:06.580 --> 28:13.300
So that's also a great way from the publicity side of things, because I think funding has been a bit of an issue for her.

28:13.300 --> 28:17.280
So hopefully this way she can get her name out more properly and further.

28:17.280 --> 28:22.020
I'm saying, I don't give a **** you can ask for 30 euros for that.

28:22.020 --> 28:24.980
I don't give a f- I will buy it, I need it.

28:24.980 --> 28:35.300
And I would really like if they did like, a little charity kind of thing, where some proceeds go through, go to woman support or something, because I think that would be beautiful.

28:35.300 --> 28:39.160
But Lego is capitalist and they ain't doing anything for me.

28:39.160 --> 28:46.960
So we move on to Rodin, who I think have one of the most interesting lineups, actually, because they will be doing things.

28:46.960 --> 28:51.380
But everyone will not expect them to be doing things, especially Emma Feblermayr.

28:51.380 --> 28:57.100
because, you know, she won last season technically twice, but she got disqualified once.

28:57.100 --> 28:58.320
That was kind of difficult.

28:58.320 --> 29:01.340
But she's with Audi again at 19.

29:01.340 --> 29:02.720
She's doing her second season.

29:03.200 --> 29:07.680
Last season, she made her debut in single-seater racing.

29:07.680 --> 29:11.340
And I think for that, she did really, really well, actually.

29:11.340 --> 29:15.460
I mean, I think she was really on that level of like Alba Larsen.

29:15.460 --> 29:17.040
So I think we were pretty close.

29:17.040 --> 29:24.280
Yeah, and it's a bit unfair to measure them against the likes of maybe Ella Lloyd or Alisha Palmowski who had experience before.

29:24.280 --> 29:27.120
They weren't complete rookies, like…

29:27.120 --> 29:28.120
I hope she's…

29:28.120 --> 29:32.060
Last year, she did Spanish F4 as a double campaign, finished 29th.

29:32.060 --> 29:39.600
Sadly, I think quite often things cut over and she didn't do a full campaign, but she was only in like very few weekends.

29:39.600 --> 29:47.960
I hope she does it again because last I remember, I think Spanish F4 does not have a single overlap with F1 Academy this season.

29:48.480 --> 29:54.660
And if she can make up the money to even go to a better team, that would be really glorious.

29:54.660 --> 29:56.360
And I would like to see it.

29:56.360 --> 29:59.340
I would like her to do things in general.

29:59.340 --> 30:04.200
But also what I want to point out, her family is involved in…

30:04.200 --> 30:08.880
I don't even know if it's considered sports cars, but I think LMP2 or LMP3.

30:08.880 --> 30:10.620
Her father and her brother drive that.

30:10.620 --> 30:16.440
So, you know, I think that if single-seaters look unlikely for her in the long term,

30:16.440 --> 30:21.560
I do hope that she at least gets to stay in racing and like in the family business.

30:21.560 --> 30:22.900
That would be great.

30:22.900 --> 30:25.540
And then moving on, Ella Lloyd is probably the…

30:25.540 --> 30:26.380
I mean, the other title…

30:26.380 --> 30:28.740
It's going to be between her and Palmowski for the title.

30:28.740 --> 30:29.160
Exactly.

30:29.160 --> 30:30.800
Backed by McLaren.

30:30.800 --> 30:33.060
And she has a lot of McLaren support.

30:33.060 --> 30:34.620
Who also…

30:34.620 --> 30:35.860
She does Formula…

30:35.860 --> 30:39.200
She did do Formula E tests with them when they were in FE.

30:39.200 --> 30:44.400
She in general has quite a lot of support, I feel like, because she has…

30:44.400 --> 30:51.180
You know, she was with McLaren FE, but now she's doing testing again with Envision in Formula E.

30:51.180 --> 30:56.120
And we saw it with Chloe Chambers and like Abbi Pulling.

30:56.120 --> 31:02.180
If they can, you know, show their worth in the testing, they can be retained.

31:02.180 --> 31:14.280
Because I remember last season, the female driver test, Chloe Chambers was faster in the first test or something than a full-season male driver.

31:14.280 --> 31:20.400
And if she can do the same, I could really see her getting a seat in…

31:20.400 --> 31:21.400
I'm sorry, that was my cat.

31:22.240 --> 31:29.640
If she can show, just like Chambers, that she's great, I think she could be getting a Formula E seat.

31:29.640 --> 31:36.820
Especially in GEN4, where there's like rumors that the cars will be even better to drive.

31:36.820 --> 31:40.200
Especially for female drivers, because they will be like power steering and stuff.

31:40.520 --> 31:45.400
So I think she's one to really watch, because of all the support that she's getting.

31:45.400 --> 31:50.360
She's also supported by every single British supporting thing.

31:50.360 --> 31:54.660
It's like British... she's like British racing stars, something.

31:54.660 --> 31:55.700
BRDC.

31:55.700 --> 31:57.740
Exactly, thank you.

31:57.740 --> 32:00.900
And she was her highest place rookie last year.

32:01.980 --> 32:04.840
Narrowly beating Palmowski, so…

32:04.840 --> 32:07.520
Like, she's performed well in British F4 as well.

32:07.520 --> 32:09.220
She was 11th with 4 podiums.

32:09.220 --> 32:12.120
I missed her podium in Zandvoort.

32:12.120 --> 32:15.860
Because I saw her race at Zandvoort in person.

32:15.860 --> 32:22.420
And I hope that I can go to Zandvoort again this year, because I expect a lot of female drivers will be doing it again.

32:22.420 --> 32:27.740
And I saw her race in person, and she was doing really, really good, actually.

32:27.740 --> 32:31.200
I can tell from my own eyes what she did.

32:31.860 --> 32:35.520
Yeah, and I think McLaren, like Mercedes, do give quite a good support.

32:35.520 --> 32:39.220
And hopefully McLaren can give that same support to Ella Stevens.

32:39.220 --> 32:42.420
Because, you know, we have the battle of the Ellas in Rodin.

32:42.420 --> 32:44.260
Can we just call them 3E?

32:44.260 --> 32:45.600
Because it's just…

32:45.600 --> 32:45.880
Yeah.

32:45.880 --> 32:46.980
Emma, Ella, Ella

32:46.980 --> 32:48.940
And Ella Hakkinen.

32:48.940 --> 32:52.080
She's not old enough yet, but she will be joining soon.

32:52.080 --> 32:55.100
We just need a team of all Ella’s, the Ella team.

32:55.100 --> 33:01.360
But I think even Emma is so close to the name Ella that I will be saying it wrong at least once this season.

33:01.480 --> 33:02.440
Ella Feblermayr.

33:02.440 --> 33:04.360
Maybe she should change her name.

33:04.360 --> 33:05.520
Yeah, but…

33:05.520 --> 33:06.480
Yeah, but Stevens.

33:06.480 --> 33:07.980
Ella Stevens.

33:07.980 --> 33:09.400
Wait, can you give me a second?

33:09.400 --> 33:11.040
I need to get my cat.

33:11.040 --> 33:13.800
Okay, so Ella Stevens.

33:13.800 --> 33:18.460
Yeah, so she is, I'd say, probably one of the most exciting rookies again.

33:18.800 --> 33:20.760
She's done really well in karting.

33:20.760 --> 33:26.020
And the fact that McLaren has picked it up alongside Ella Lloyd says quite a bit, I think.

33:26.020 --> 33:29.460
When I researched her, I found quite a lot of interesting stuff.

33:29.460 --> 33:34.620
Because she is, in general, in karting, she was rated, like, incredibly high.

33:34.740 --> 33:35.800
Like, you wouldn't believe it.

33:35.800 --> 33:36.860
She was rated so high.

33:37.700 --> 33:41.340
I found some posts from, like, before F1 Academy was a thing.

33:41.340 --> 33:42.140
That's important to me.

33:42.140 --> 33:45.700
That, like, Ferrari was, you know, looking at her.

33:45.700 --> 33:51.300
And she had the possibility of, and with Ferrari, which I don't know how much of that is true.

33:51.340 --> 33:56.480
But just the fact that they were implying that is- my cat is really annoying me right now.

33:56.480 --> 34:00.280
Just the fact that they were implying that is low-key crazy if you think about it.

34:00.280 --> 34:09.160
And she was mentioned on a list of, like, the biggest female talents to watch next to drivers like Maya Weug, Jamie Chadwick.

34:09.160 --> 34:12.560
Like, huge drivers who we know are really great.

34:12.560 --> 34:17.480
And if the rumors are true, then I think she's really, really one to watch.

34:17.640 --> 34:27.580
And she's really one who could kind of, you know, be the standout rookie that no one kind of expected Emma and Alba to be last season.

34:27.580 --> 34:34.660
Even if she's not winning the championship, I think she could, maybe she could go away with a podium or win at some point.

34:34.660 --> 34:37.860
Yeah, because she has never raced F4 before.

34:37.860 --> 34:43.300
So, as you said, like Larsen last year, she's a complete newbie.

34:43.560 --> 34:51.500
She is very exciting and although she's a bit on the older side, she is the sort of driver who F1 Academy has made for,

34:51.500 --> 34:54.780
their first F4 experience and it's going to be fun.

34:54.780 --> 34:57.140
I wish we could have picked her up sooner.

34:57.140 --> 34:58.710
It would have been so glorious.

34:58.710 --> 34:59.940
It would have been so beautiful.

34:59.940 --> 35:03.020
Even 2 years ago, even for like 2024.

35:03.840 --> 35:07.820
I mean, I've said it, it's not like she's just come into karting.

35:07.820 --> 35:11.500
She's been rated as a female karting driver for many years.

35:11.500 --> 35:14.040
Even before F1 Academy was a thing.

35:14.040 --> 35:16.320
Even like years ago, it was like posts about.

35:16.320 --> 35:20.460
“Oh my God, there's this 12-year-old driving cars and she's really good at it.”

35:20.460 --> 35:23.860
And it would have been great to see her be picked up sooner.

35:23.860 --> 35:29.060
But I hope that's something that we can improve for the next few F1 Academy seasons.

35:29.060 --> 35:31.210
Because we are already going down, girl.

35:31.210 --> 35:35.880
You know, he literally had a BBC article made about her in 2018.

35:35.880 --> 35:37.380
That's what I mean.

35:37.380 --> 35:41.440
Like she's like 12 and I was like, oh my God, this is 12-year-old.

35:41.440 --> 35:42.040
She's like.

35:42.040 --> 35:43.260
Yeah, when she was 11.

35:43.260 --> 35:44.210
Oh my God.

35:44.210 --> 35:47.690
Is she 12? Is she 11? It's such a difference, I'm sorry.

35:47.690 --> 35:50.170
I'm so sorry for every 12-year-old out there.

35:50.170 --> 35:51.660
Moving on.

35:52.060 --> 35:54.780
So we're always talking about old drivers.

35:54.780 --> 36:01.860
How about we talk about a team where we cannot, under any circumstances, complain about the age?

36:01.860 --> 36:06.600
ART with the lineup of Kaylee Countryman, Jade Jacquet and Lisa Billard.

36:06.600 --> 36:10.560
16-year-old, which is the youngest you can be in this.

36:10.560 --> 36:14.100
You have to be 16 due to the need for an international license.

36:14.640 --> 36:21.210
Also, Kaylee and Jade, I'm pretty sure, only turned 16 pretty recently.

36:21.210 --> 36:28.710
Because I swear, Kaylee turned 16 this year and Jade turned 16 like November or December last year.

36:28.710 --> 36:32.920
So that's like really the youngest that you can get around here.

36:32.920 --> 36:39.230
Like you can't get any younger pretty much because then you have to like, you know, not race because you're too young.

36:39.230 --> 36:42.730
Cause unfortunately, you do have to be 16, not 15.

36:42.730 --> 36:46.210
But yeah, Kaylee Countryman is the youngest driver.

36:46.210 --> 36:52.280
She has come from doing USF2000, which is on that road to Indy ladder.

36:52.280 --> 36:55.060
Sponsored by Haas, proper American, I guess.

36:55.060 --> 36:59.480
Yeah, I think it's really interesting because if Cadillac had come in this season already,
,
36:59.480 --> 37:03.600
I think she would have probably been picked up by Cadillac.

37:03.600 --> 37:05.190
Just like, I mean, it's a great thing.

37:05.190 --> 37:10.160
I think even if she's not like going into the F1 road of things,

37:10.160 --> 37:16.920
because she's also doing USF, is she doing USF Juniors or USF2000 this season?

37:16.920 --> 37:21.120
I think she's USF Juniors last year and she's doing USF2000.

37:21.120 --> 37:29.120
I'd also be really glad if we had, you know, a female IndyCar driver soon.

37:29.670 --> 37:37.560
Definitely, and like road to Indy is great in the way that, you know, it's very kind of more natural progression, I'd say, compared to the F1 ladder.

37:37.560 --> 37:42.690
So, and doing F1 Academy just gets you that all important track time.

37:43.260 --> 37:57.710
The only worry that I have about her is that she's coming from America and we've seen it, that making that step from America to, I mean, it's not really European because we're like all over the world.

37:57.710 --> 38:10.160
But I could imagine that the way that F1 Academy feels European and the way that they race like most European F4s, you know, the car is used heavily in Europe.

38:10.380 --> 38:15.670
And all the teams, all the teams are based in Europe.

38:15.670 --> 38:26.560
And I could imagine that this could really put her on a back foot because you have drivers like Jade Jacquet and Lisa Billard who are like French, and ART is French.

38:26.710 --> 38:30.280
Like, you know, they can be much more directly at the team.

38:30.280 --> 38:35.260
They have a much more direct way of communicating with, you know, the team.

38:35.260 --> 38:41.210
They can test, they test with FFSA.

38:41.210 --> 38:53.190
Kaylee Countryman has to fly to Europe every time if she like wants to use a European simulator, which I assume ART has.

38:53.670 --> 39:01.320
And then she has to probably fly back to America with a race in America, which is kind of really impractical if you think about it.

39:01.320 --> 39:06.620
But then on the flip side, she could get a really good experience in Europe and take it over to America.

39:06.620 --> 39:12.660
I've seen the drivers coming from maybe F2, F3 and then going to America and they can perform really well.

39:12.660 --> 39:16.080
So it could help her in the long run as well, I would say.

39:16.080 --> 39:21.170
Yeah, I think the track time and also the funding will be really, really good for her.

39:21.780 --> 39:28.620
And I think the one thing that I'm worrying about is does Haas have a simulator now?

39:28.620 --> 39:32.880
I remember back in 2024, they did not have one.

39:32.880 --> 39:36.860
And I'm worried that they still don't have a simulator.

39:36.860 --> 39:39.000
I hope they have a simulator.

39:39.000 --> 39:46.400
She really has the disadvantage that Haas is like from, you know, supporting the drivers.

39:46.400 --> 39:50.820
They're a small team that's difficult for them, which is really sad.

39:50.820 --> 39:57.360
And it will not help her in comparison to Jade Jacquet, who was supported by Williams.

39:57.360 --> 40:01.040
Yeah, so she was in French F4 last year.

40:01.040 --> 40:12.280
Unfortunately, even if she was old enough, when she turned 16 to do F1 Academy, she wasn't able to, as they annoyingly don't allow double campaigns.

40:12.600 --> 40:15.670
Didn't she turn 16 like in November or December?

40:15.670 --> 40:17.560
Not too sure.

40:17.560 --> 40:24.580
Because I swear, I remember reading something at the Williams website that she just turned 16 very recently.

40:24.580 --> 40:25.800
Oh yeah.

40:25.800 --> 40:28.380
December of 2009.

40:29.380 --> 40:41.480
The problem with French F4 is really that they do not allow double campaigns, which I think is sad, especially this season, because she will only be able to do F1 Academy.

40:41.480 --> 40:46.820
When I think doing a second season in French F4 could really be good for her.

40:46.820 --> 40:52.230
Because luckily, FFSA at least lets them test with them, which I think is great.

40:52.230 --> 40:54.020
And what are you going to understand?

40:54.020 --> 40:55.780
Let them race then, FFSA.

40:55.780 --> 40:57.460
Let them race, please.

40:57.460 --> 41:10.800
What you got to understand about FFSA is that they're like simultaneously, they do the French F4 championship, but also they are kind of like the French version , of what's BRDC?

41:11.420 --> 41:17.420
Or even more serious than that, because like their name is always on the cars and they support drivers.

41:17.420 --> 41:23.170
They have like the FFSA Academy, which I still don't quite know what that is, but we will figure it out.

41:23.170 --> 41:25.000
And they do a lot.

41:25.000 --> 41:29.500
And French drivers are really advantaged and really lucky to get that kind of support.

41:29.940 --> 41:36.560
I just really don't understand why you cannot have them race somewhere else, too, you know?

41:36.560 --> 41:41.340
Yeah, because you don't, ultimately in F1 Academy, you don't get that much track time.

41:41.340 --> 41:44.880
So it's so important to be able to do another series, I believe.

41:44.880 --> 41:49.520
And I mean, it's not like French F4 did not have women.

41:49.520 --> 41:51.670
Like last season, I think they had four or five women.

41:51.670 --> 42:03.100
So I think, wouldn't it be better if we supported women who are like, really doing stuff and moving up and getting more sponsors to, you know, also continue their path here?

42:03.100 --> 42:14.800
That's a bit sad, but it's sadly also the same for Lisa Billard, who's like, to me, one of the standout names if we talk about women in single-seater racing.

42:14.800 --> 42:21.480
Because for some reason, she's like on that list of women that always get mentioned when you talk about women in single-seater racing.

42:21.820 --> 42:25.020
Yeah, unfortunately, though, she's not supported by an F1 team.

42:25.020 --> 42:26.710
She's sponsored by Gatorade.

42:26.710 --> 42:28.360
Really surprised me about that.

42:28.360 --> 42:35.520
I know she was in the Aston Martin shootout and she was like pretty far off Matilda Paatz, which also really surprised me.

42:35.520 --> 42:40.120
But I thought, and I was really sure, she would be getting on with Mercedes.

42:40.120 --> 42:43.520
Yeah, there's nothing stopping these teams from having two drivers.

42:43.520 --> 42:46.280
I mean, McLaren has two, well, three eventually.

42:46.280 --> 42:49.880
So, I mean, it's a shame that it's just Gatorade,
 
42:50.000 --> 42:53.320
because especially if it's one with the bigger teams, you have those facilities.

42:53.320 --> 42:55.280
You can be such a help to the driver.

42:55.280 --> 42:57.880
And worst of all, she's also at ART.

42:57.880 --> 43:00.600
And what is going on at ART?

43:00.600 --> 43:05.160
Like, in the last seasons, they were usually by far, like, the worst.

43:05.160 --> 43:08.340
It's, I really worry for her because I think, just talent-wise,

43:08.340 --> 43:15.540
she would, she should be, like, on the level of, like, I'd expect her to be, like, on the level of, like, Alba Larsen, you know, Feblermayr.

43:15.540 --> 43:21.020
But with, you know, the way that she's, the team she's in, Gatorade is a sponsor.

43:21.020 --> 43:22.280
What's Gatorade going to do?

43:22.280 --> 43:23.460
They can give her a drink.

43:23.460 --> 43:25.670
They can't give her, like, sim sessions or anything.

43:25.670 --> 43:29.440
It'd be in her drink spotter during the race, you know, the Gatorade will fuel her.

43:29.440 --> 43:31.860
It's going to give her that extra superpowers.

43:32.900 --> 43:33.690
Wait, give me a minute.

43:33.690 --> 43:38.480
Uh, my cat just tried to, you know, we talk about Aston Martin too much.

43:38.480 --> 43:42.540
My cat just tried to take, uh, my sister’s Aston Martin car.

43:42.540 --> 43:45.560
Gatorade is not even a common drink in France.

43:45.560 --> 43:47.540
So why is Gatorade?

43:47.540 --> 43:50.460
I mean, I don't even know how this connection happened.

43:50.460 --> 43:53.520
I'm pretty sure Gatorade was banned in Germany.

43:53.520 --> 43:56.780
I've never seen it before in the UK.

43:56.780 --> 43:59.120
I've, like, never tried it before.

43:59.960 --> 44:06.960
Is it possible that it's just really unpopular in Europe because it's emotionally American to me?

44:06.960 --> 44:11.600
Um, I could imagine it's, like, not a European thing.

44:11.600 --> 44:18.760
But let's move on to another team that is not known for providing the best of cars.

44:18.760 --> 44:23.020
Hitech with Ava Dobson and Rachel Robertson.

44:23.020 --> 44:28.060
Because, of course, their third driver is normally their, uh, wild car driver with Hitech.

44:28.280 --> 44:28.700
Exactly.

44:28.700 --> 44:34.940
Um, for Ava Dobson, I think it's going to be really interesting because she has done quite a lot already.

44:34.940 --> 44:38.360
She was, uh, majorly doing stuff in the US.

44:38.360 --> 44:42.760
But it's really hard for me to rate anything that happens in the US.

44:42.760 --> 44:48.100
Because sometimes you have really great, uh, grids in the US.

44:48.100 --> 44:50.040
You know, great drivers.

44:50.040 --> 44:51.200
And they really fight.

44:51.200 --> 44:52.740
And other times, you don't.

44:52.920 --> 44:54.560
And we've seen the example.

44:54.560 --> 45:02.480
Like, we had, uh, Nicole Havrda last season who finished, I think, sixth in, um, Formula Regional America.

45:02.480 --> 45:04.600
Like, above F4.

45:04.600 --> 45:07.860
And she was, like, by far one of the worst F1 Academy drivers.

45:07.860 --> 45:09.660
So I think it's hard to judge that.

45:09.660 --> 45:13.140
I think it really just depends on how they adapt.

45:13.480 --> 45:15.900
Why does my cat want to eat the Aston Martin?

45:15.900 --> 45:17.740
He's sending you a message.

45:17.740 --> 45:20.620
So, um, she switched to GB4.

45:20.620 --> 45:23.300
Which is, I think, kind of more possible to rate.

45:23.300 --> 45:25.600
And she was really, really close to Megan Bruce.

45:25.600 --> 45:26.520
Like, the whole season.

45:26.520 --> 45:29.160
She only won the female driver's trophy.

45:29.160 --> 45:32.520
Because, uh, she did one weekend more.

45:32.520 --> 45:34.640
Because, you know, Megan missed it.

45:34.640 --> 45:35.840
Because of Singapore.

45:35.840 --> 45:39.500
And I don't have a lot to say about her, honestly.

45:39.500 --> 45:41.840
Because I cannot really rate her.

45:41.840 --> 45:42.580
Wait a minute.

45:42.580 --> 45:43.520
I need to get my cat-

45:43.520 --> 45:45.200
Okay.

45:45.200 --> 45:46.240
Ava Dobson.

45:46.240 --> 45:49.480
I do not really know how to rate her.

45:49.480 --> 45:51.100
And what to expect of her.

45:51.580 --> 46:03.260
Because I almost worry that she could, like, be one of the really markers we had with, like, Nicole Havrida, Aiva Anagnostiadis, and Joanne Ciconte last season.

46:03.260 --> 46:05.780
Because she's also supported by Amex.

46:05.780 --> 46:10.220
And with Hitech, I don't think she's in the best position to get anywhere.

46:10.220 --> 46:11.060
Because.

46:11.060 --> 46:14.200
Unless with Amex they pay for a really good engine.

46:14.200 --> 46:17.300
But, like, even last year with Nicole Havrida.

46:17.300 --> 46:21.080
Do we remember in, was it Las Vegas, which was the last round?

46:21.380 --> 46:23.120
Where she had a special livery..

46:23.120 --> 46:25.860
And no one mentioned it until after the race.

46:25.860 --> 46:26.960
And I was watching her.

46:26.960 --> 46:30.800
And I was like, that's not, that's not the usual car we have on the screen.

46:30.800 --> 46:32.440
Like, what's happening here?

46:32.440 --> 46:33.620
No one mentioned it.

46:33.620 --> 46:36.100
It was just, and it was a really nice livery, too.

46:36.100 --> 46:36.900
That was horrible.

46:36.900 --> 46:38.600
I was really disappointed.

46:38.600 --> 46:45.300
And then, like, Ava Dobson, Rachel Robertson also did not have an F1 team supporting her.

46:45.300 --> 46:47.520
Instead, she is sponsored by Puma.

46:47.520 --> 46:50.160
At least they're sports-related and not AMEX.

46:50.700 --> 46:53.440
Puma at least can give her shoes.

46:53.440 --> 46:54.600
Racing boots.

46:54.600 --> 47:02.980
There's all kinds, if you've seen the posts by Aurelia Noble that she had, like, 20 pairs of Puma shoes because she always gets them.

47:02.980 --> 47:04.700
Which I think is kind of hilarious.

47:05.320 --> 47:08.720
She had a decent showing in Vegas last year in the sprint.

47:08.720 --> 47:10.720
She finished fourth, so.

47:11.100 --> 47:19.220
I often mix up Esmee Kosterman and her because both of them have kind of done, like, these weird series.

47:19.220 --> 47:24.420
She's done the Radical Cup UK, which someone tried to explain it to me, but I still don't quite know what it is.

47:24.420 --> 47:30.340
But to me, it just shows these drivers, they don't just, you know, try to go the linear path.

47:30.440 --> 47:31.980
And if it doesn't work, you know, they give up.

47:31.980 --> 47:35.100
But they drive everything that you give them.

47:35.100 --> 47:36.540
You can put them in everything.

47:36.540 --> 47:37.280
They would try it.

47:37.280 --> 47:40.040
And I think on its simultaneous, it's really beautiful.

47:40.040 --> 47:43.060
And it really shows to me that it's real interest in racing.

47:43.220 --> 47:45.060
And there's this huge, really, interest.

47:45.060 --> 47:47.240
And they're willing to fight for it.

47:47.240 --> 47:48.560
And they're willing to do anything.

47:48.560 --> 47:50.960
And they're willing to try anything as long as they get to race.

47:50.960 --> 47:59.700
But simultaneously, it's so sad to me because why I'll be keeping potentially great drivers in these series just because they're a woman.

47:59.700 --> 48:01.080
It's, you know, it's sad.

48:01.080 --> 48:04.060
I think, I really hope that she does well.

48:04.060 --> 48:08.220
But what we just said about Ava Dobson also counts for her.

48:08.220 --> 48:09.380
She's with Puma.

48:09.380 --> 48:11.100
She's with Hitech.

48:11.360 --> 48:17.280
I hope Hitech as a team can make a step up from last season because they seem really disoriented at some point.

48:17.280 --> 48:18.980
You know, it was their first season.

48:18.980 --> 48:20.920
They didn't have any experience before that.

48:20.920 --> 48:26.680
But other than that, I don't expect quite a lot of her, sadly.

48:26.680 --> 48:30.540
There's generally low expectations for Hitech, I mean.

48:30.540 --> 48:33.820
But it's not because I don't rate them as drivers.

48:33.820 --> 48:36.000
It's just that I think we need to be honest.

48:36.480 --> 48:48.580
A driver in PREMA with an F1 team backing will always have more advantages and more, you know, possibilities to get somewhere than a driver in Hitech with no team sponsor.

48:48.580 --> 48:52.300
And, you know, no support when it comes to simulators.

48:52.300 --> 48:55.280
No support when it comes to, like, training and stuff.

48:55.860 --> 48:59.840
Yeah, I mean, I feel like that's everything I have to hear about the drivers.

48:59.840 --> 49:03.720
But the calendar is looking quite interesting, I think.

49:03.720 --> 49:09.420
Excitingly, we have both Silverstone and the Circuit of the Americas returning, which are…

49:09.420 --> 49:10.440
I love COTA.

49:10.900 --> 49:13.500
It's honestly one of my favourite tracks, apart from Silverstone.

49:13.500 --> 49:19.060
And Silverstone, I am biased, there is a bit of, you know, patriotism associated with it.

49:19.060 --> 49:29.560
I mean, I feel like I know that we cannot race on a lot of, like, the usual circuits because it's already so filled with a Porsche Cup, F2, F3.

49:30.040 --> 49:38.620
But if we have to race in different circuits, then at least, please, at least give me circuits like COTA because I expect COTA to be great.

49:38.620 --> 49:44.080
We had it in 2023 already, and I swear it was good.

49:44.080 --> 49:45.100
It was nice.

49:45.100 --> 49:47.960
It was definitely better than Miami.

49:47.960 --> 49:48.900
Yeah.

49:48.900 --> 49:53.740
I mean, they're placing Miami and Singapore, which ultimately just aren't suited for F4 cars.

49:54.180 --> 49:58.280
But COTA could also, I don't know, has Kaylee Countryman raced at COTA?

49:58.280 --> 50:01.440
But I think COTA is just like an American circuit.

50:01.440 --> 50:10.160
So even if she has not raced it, she should be able to, you know, be used to the way that American circuits usually behave.

50:10.160 --> 50:13.440
If you can say it like that, like the way the tracks…

50:13.440 --> 50:18.280
What's the word for the stuff that's on the ground, the fabric?

50:18.280 --> 50:19.640
The asphalt.

50:19.640 --> 50:20.780
The asphalt.

50:20.780 --> 50:23.380
You know, she's used to the way the asphalt behaves.
 
50:23.460 --> 50:27.120
She's used to the way that the weather behaves and weather and the asphalt mix up.

50:27.120 --> 50:31.300
She's probably used to how to treat tyres.

50:31.300 --> 50:36.820
I think a great thing about Silverstone and COTA is you just get so much publicity.

50:36.820 --> 50:39.300
Like, there'll be so much support at Silverstone.

50:39.300 --> 50:41.220
I hope, like, I was there this year.

50:41.220 --> 50:45.540
And last time, even for the F4 races, there were some people showing up.

50:45.540 --> 50:46.980
So I hope for the…

50:46.980 --> 50:53.420
Silverstone, we could look at it if British F4 drives on Silverstone.

50:53.460 --> 50:58.760
Because I could imagine drivers looking at doing the same as they did with Zandford.

50:59.300 --> 51:08.360
Again, I expect a lot of drivers to go to Zandvoort for the British F4 round again and, you know, gain a bit of track.

51:08.360 --> 51:09.760
gain a bit of experience.

51:09.940 --> 51:15.440
And I would love as many F1 team sponsors back to that as possible.

51:15.440 --> 51:17.480
Because I think it's a great thing.

51:17.480 --> 51:19.760
I think it's amazing to do stuff like that.

51:20.280 --> 51:26.520
Unfortunately, firstly, I just want to say that we hope everyone stays safe.

51:26.520 --> 51:33.940
And, of course, we're seeing it's not the biggest priority, given what is currently happening in the Middle East at the moment.

51:33.940 --> 51:38.220
And our thoughts are with everyone currently affected by the conflict.

51:38.620 --> 51:47.580
But due to the current situation, it probably means that Jeddah, which is scheduled for April in about a month's time, is going to get cancelled.

51:47.580 --> 51:52.060
I mean, if things were perfect, the war would, like, end right now.

51:52.060 --> 51:53.440
No one would get hurt.

51:53.700 --> 51:59.420
And, you know, everyone would kind of get a result in which they're happy, in which no one gets hurt anymore.

51:59.420 --> 52:08.960
But sadly, we do not live in my utopic idea of everyone has the life that they not just deserve, but that they want to have.

52:08.960 --> 52:13.300
And it's really majorly just horrible for the people.

52:13.300 --> 52:16.320
And I almost feel bad for mentioning it.

52:16.460 --> 52:23.040
But for our racing series, it obviously means they're not going to be able to race there.

52:23.040 --> 52:30.300
And especially if we talk about F1 Academy, we have a limit in how much teams can spend.

52:30.300 --> 52:36.980
So while I would love to see them race somewhere else, I would obviously race somewhere else in general.

52:36.980 --> 52:41.120
But it's just not a possibility this season.

52:41.240 --> 52:47.480
Because I think the limit is £100,000 that, you know, it can cost as much.

52:47.480 --> 52:53.020
I don't know if, like, hotels and, you know, transport is included in that.

52:53.020 --> 52:54.000
And I doubt it.

52:54.000 --> 52:58.360
But for the seat itself, it's £100,000 or around £100,000.

52:58.360 --> 53:04.860
The thing is, if you were to now say, hey, we go to Brazil instead and we go to, like, São Paulo.

53:04.860 --> 53:06.020
I love São Paulo.
53:06.020 --> 53:09.300
I think it's one of those circuits that I would love to see them race at.

53:09.580 --> 53:13.700
It just gets so expensive for the whole series to go there.

53:13.700 --> 53:19.600
And with the other European F1 rounds, unfortunately, just the calendar doesn't work out.

53:19.600 --> 53:25.780
Because on pretty much, I think with all the other European circuits, you have F2, F3 and Porsche Cup.

53:25.780 --> 53:30.580
And there's no way, unfortunately, the schedule can fit in five different series.

53:30.580 --> 53:33.000
That is just a bit too unpractical.

53:33.320 --> 53:35.760
Even if they could fit it, I don't think they would.

53:35.760 --> 53:43.720
Because you have to consider the cost of F1 Academy having to transport all of their stuff there.

53:43.940 --> 53:56.320
Because usually, I assume that even if you have, like, a month's break, you don't ship stuff back to, like, the country where they're originally located at.

53:56.320 --> 54:02.280
Because what I know from F1 logistics, at least, it's, like, look at the calendar.

54:02.280 --> 54:04.700
We race, obviously, in America twice.

54:04.700 --> 54:11.880
But there's almost a month between it in end of October at and end of November in Las Vegas.

54:11.880 --> 54:16.340
And technically, technically, they could ship cars back in time.

54:16.340 --> 54:18.880
But obviously, that's a stupid *** idea.

54:18.880 --> 54:21.320
So, you know, they won't be doing it.

54:21.320 --> 54:27.720
They will be putting the cars on, probably, trucks and sending it down to Las Vegas already.

54:27.720 --> 54:34.400
So, unfortunately, this means, for me, the F1 Academy calendar is already limited with only 14 races.

54:34.400 --> 54:38.180
And ultimately, we'll just be down to six rounds with 12 races.

54:38.180 --> 54:42.500
Unless they maybe add additional races elsewhere, that is also possible.

54:42.500 --> 54:47.360
Like, we saw in Canada last year they had three races, 3 getting cancelled in Miami.   

54:47.360 --> 54:49.740
But it is a bit of a shame overall.

54:49.740 --> 54:53.500
Like, Jeddah has generally been a bit of a fun circuit, I feel like.

54:53.500 --> 54:57.620
But, of course, that is not the biggest priority at the moment.

54:58.040 --> 55:04.940
But I think now that we've kind of covered the calendar, one last thing that I wanted to talk about F1 Academy in general.

55:04.940 --> 55:08.060
Just to, you know, lighten the mood a bit again.

55:08.060 --> 55:09.700
To talk about positive things.

55:09.700 --> 55:11.640
It's the 8th of March.

55:11.640 --> 55:13.940
It's the International Women's Day.

55:13.940 --> 55:19.800
And I think if we talk about women in motorsport, people often like to criticize F1 Academy.

55:19.960 --> 55:21.920
There's also a lot that I could criticize.

55:21.920 --> 55:29.500
But I want to take the chance, I want to take the day, and also kind of think about the good things that F1 Academy has already done.

55:29.500 --> 55:33.780
And the good ways that F1 Academy has already impacted drivers.

55:33.780 --> 55:39.020
You know, we talked about GB4 having the Female Driver Trophy now.

55:39.180 --> 55:50.640
And maybe in the future, that Female Driver Trophy could be changed from just the money being just used for F1 Academy to the money going to any further racing series.

55:50.640 --> 55:59.180
If a driver wins or gets runner-up in GB4 again, why not use that money to afford a GB3 season?

55:59.180 --> 56:02.080
But, you know, there's something that can happen now.

56:02.080 --> 56:10.040
Because someone put the foot down and said, we see F1 Academy, we see this huge rise in numbers of female drivers.

56:10.360 --> 56:18.600
I think this season, you can hardly go into any single Formula 4 without seeing at least one, usually more, female names.

56:18.600 --> 56:24.860
I've been already thinking about the wild card drivers, and it's so hard to choose because there's so many drivers.

56:24.860 --> 56:26.820
There's so many drivers doing things.

56:26.820 --> 56:28.960
There's so many drivers getting into F4.

56:28.960 --> 56:31.400
There's so many drivers, you know, trying their hands.

56:31.400 --> 56:32.660
I saw the numbers.

56:32.660 --> 56:40.340
There's over 100%, I think it was like 400% or something, rise in female participation in parting races.

56:40.340 --> 56:43.260
And it's such a great thing to see.

56:43.260 --> 56:51.980
And we see it with the drivers that we talked about today already, that we have drivers who wanted to race and who, you know, look for this opportunity.

56:51.980 --> 57:01.140
And for drivers who cannot really afford to just go into any F4 series because they're not, you know, loaded as, you know, crazy loaded.

57:01.140 --> 57:06.160
For them, it's finally the opportunity to do an F4 series.

57:06.160 --> 57:13.920
And I mean, we had that one great, great commentary thing in UA4, which I always think about.

57:13.920 --> 57:15.640
And it's even applicable here.

57:15.640 --> 57:22.540
You know, I sadly don't think we have the path yet to go from F1 Academy to F1.

57:22.540 --> 57:27.240
And so, you know, not all of them will magically end up in F1.

57:27.240 --> 57:32.200
Maybe we will be lucky and see some of them make it, especially of the younger people.

57:32.200 --> 57:40.140
But much more importantly, I think we will see a rise in female involvement all across the series.

57:40.360 --> 57:48.320
We see a rise in Formula E already with the female drivers test, with female drivers just being ever present at the rookie tests.

57:48.320 --> 57:53.540
Now, I think recently it was only announced that Ella Lloyd would join Envision again.

57:53.540 --> 58:01.840
And Abbi Pulling is expected to join Nissan again and probably Mahindra with Chloe Chambers.

58:02.100 --> 58:16.380
We see huge rise in female drivers across GT series, not just with Iron Dames, but there's also a girls only team in the Nürngring Endurance series.

58:16.380 --> 58:21.380
We see it with the drivers that have, you know, come from the series to make their path.

58:21.380 --> 58:28.680
Now, well, so even if it's not F1 and even if we talk about F3 and F2, F1 won't be the end for a lot of them.

58:28.680 --> 58:33.880
But it will be other series and you have Doriane Pin doing LMP2 now again.

58:33.880 --> 58:37.300
You have Chloe Chambers probably making this step through ET.

58:37.300 --> 58:42.660
It reminds me of what Sanson was saying on the F4 broadcast, remember?

58:42.660 --> 58:45.760
It's just what I was referencing because it's beautiful.

58:45.760 --> 58:49.920
Hopefully we'll see Cade Countryman join the Indy 500.

58:49.920 --> 58:54.280
And we have Dorian Pinn doing the 24 hours of Le Mans.

58:54.280 --> 59:00.440
And we can have someone else hopefully soon make it to F1 and FE.

59:00.440 --> 59:02.740
And I'm running out of series I can mention.

59:02.740 --> 59:08.940
Super Formula, you know, Joanne Ciconte, last season made it to Kyojo Cup and is now racing in Japan.

59:08.940 --> 59:09.820
Why not?

59:09.820 --> 59:10.880
Let's f***ing go.

59:12.320 --> 59:16.920
Before we, you know, finish up, I want to ask for your prediction, Peter.

59:16.920 --> 59:18.500
What is your prediction?

59:18.500 --> 59:20.880
We can do it in the same way that F1 Academy did.

59:20.880 --> 59:22.200
Who do you think will be?

59:22.200 --> 59:26.760
Teams champion, drivers champion, best rookie and biggest standout?

59:26.760 --> 59:30.100
Teams champion is going to be Rodin, I think.

59:30.100 --> 59:32.060
Champion, Palmowski.

59:32.060 --> 59:34.280
Highest rookie…

59:34.280 --> 59:38.200
I think probably Ella Stevens.

59:38.200 --> 59:39.780
And biggest standout?

59:40.520 --> 59:44.140
Standout, is going, can I repeat drivers or should I say someone else?

59:44.140 --> 59:48.360
Yeah, obviously you can also say group of drivers or team or…

59:48.360 --> 59:54.380
I think actually, can I say, like, I'm not going to say, aside from the title fight being Palmowski and Lloyd.

59:54.380 --> 59:57.040
I think Larsen had kind of a breakout here as well.

59:57.040 --> 59:59.560
So I definitely agree with Rodin.

59:59.560 --> 01:00:01.840
I think they have the strongest lineup in general.

01:00:01.840 --> 01:00:08.840
I think, obviously, I'm going to be, for the title fight, it's going to be Palmowski.

01:00:09.720 --> 01:00:12.600
And you all will see me on Twitter going hardcore for this.

01:00:12.600 --> 01:00:18.700
For the highest rookie, I think I'll be biased and I'll go for Matilda Paatz.

01:00:18.700 --> 01:00:23.700
And for the biggest standout, I'm going to say it's going to be the wildcard drivers this year.

01:00:23.700 --> 01:00:28.820
Because I think, especially in Silverstone, I expect something.

01:00:28.820 --> 01:00:31.720
Silverstone is going to be a great weekend because…

01:00:31.720 --> 01:00:36.160
The vibe there, at the race, everybody's so supportive, so nice.

01:00:36.160 --> 01:00:40.840
And it's going to be great to get that sort of attention on F1 Academy.

01:00:40.840 --> 01:00:44.200
And, again, the series is great for them attracting sponsors.

01:00:44.200 --> 01:00:49.040
Hopefully, you know, sponsors will see them doing well and get them more funding.

01:00:49.040 --> 01:00:50.340
And, yeah.

01:00:51.300 --> 01:00:55.920
Anyways, I think that'll be it for this episode of the Grand Prequel Pod.

01:00:55.920 --> 01:01:02.320
Be sure to give us a follow on Twitter, Instagram, and TikTok, @grandprequel.

